<h1>@HI{{suruto}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @HI{{@EM{{suruto}}}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
@HI{{@EM{{suruto}}}} is a conjunction that joins two sentences. The second of the two either describes an event that
occurs immediately after the first sentence or expresses a logical guess related to it.
</p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{jogingu}}wo@KJ{{commence}}memashita. @EM{{suruto}}go@KJ{{meal}}gaoishikunarimashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I began jogging. Then I began to have a good appetite.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      A: @HI{{@KJ{{now^day}}ha@KJ{{month^weekday^day}}desuyo.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      B: @HI{{@EM{{suruto}}ano@KT{{depa-to}}ha@KJ{{rest}}midesune.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      A: Today's Monday you know.
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      B: Then that department store is closed isn't it?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
The @HI{{to}} in @HI{{@EM{{suruto}}}} is the <a href="grammar-to-conditional.html">@HI{{to}} conditional</a>,
so the second sentence normally expresses something beyond the control of the speaker and cannot be a command, request or suggestion.
</p>

